Jean Batten Plans to Reach Sydney Tomorrow STILL INTENDS TO REACH NEW ZEALAND IN NINE DAYS Civil Aviation Board to Ascertain Maximum Load for Plane MUST COMPLY WITH REGULATIONS SYDNEY, Monday. Jean Batten, who left Darwin today on her record-breaking solo flight from England, expects to reach Sydney from Charleville, where she will stay tonight, about 10 a.m. tomorrow. It is still her intention to reach New Zealand in nine days from London, but Civil Aviation Department regulations may prevent her flying the Tasman Eea. It was proposed that the Civil Aviation Board should meet in Melbourne today to discuss the question of allowing Miss Batten to take off for New Zealand; But as no direct action can be taken to prevent the flight if her lane complies with regulations it was decided that a was not necessary.

ENGLISH CRICKET TOUR MANAGER. Appointment of Mr. Harold Bushby. BOARD OF CONTROL'S IMPORTANT DECISIONS. Mr. Harold Bushby, Tasmanian representative on the Board of Control, yesterday was appointed manager of the Australian cricket eleven, which will leave Fremantle on March 26 for London. Allowances to the manager, treasurer, and players will be the same as those for the 1930 tour. The Board of Control agreed that the Test matches should be limited to four days, the fifth to be played outright if the fate of the "ashes" depends upon the result.  SYDNEY, September 22.

Catholic Relief Pours into Stricken Flood Areas LONDON (By Air Mail), Feb. 15. "Practical, Spontaneous and Universal" Response From Vatican City and from Catholic Action organizations in Europe and America relief in money and goods is pouring into the flood areas of Holand, Belgium and Britain. In addition, relief teams have been rushed to the evacuee centres and were at work there within a few days of the catastrophe. The speedy mobilization of resources by the French Catholic Aid organization, Secours Catholique, and Italy's Catholic Action, together with the instant and efficacious response of the Pontifical Assistance Commission, has greatly impressed the whole populations of the stricken countries. In Sydney the St. Vincent de Paul Society is handling the relief appeal and in Melbourne the Catholic Welfare Organization has already sent a shipment of goods and, as reported last week, is urgently appealing for clothing, tinned foods, and donations in cash. From Our London Correspondent
